  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) Requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Documenting customer information\n\n2. Transaction Monitoring\n- Tracking suspicious financial activities\n- Reporting unusual transactions\n- Identifying potential money laundering patterns\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Submitting Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Implementing anti-money laundering (AML) programs\n- Conducting periodic risk assessments\n- Training employees on detection methods\n\n5. International Regulations\n- Complying with global anti-money laundering standards\n- Participating in international information sharing\n- Following recommendations from Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n\n6. Reporting Obligations\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Disclosing potential criminal financial activities\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\nFinancial institutions can face significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges, for failing to meet these obligations.",
